            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the weight of the keys his father placed in his palm. He was nineteen. The brass was cool against his skin, heavy with the promise of opening the deli before dawn. The scent of coffee and yeast from the bakery next door filled the morning air. In that moment, he wasn't just Marco Bianchi; he was the future of his family, the keeper of their small corner of North Beach. It was a feeling of pride so profound, it felt like standing on top of the world.\n\n2.\nThe last day at the deli didn\u2019t smell of salami and provolone, but of bleach and regret. After sweeping the floor one final time, he turned the lock. In the glass, he saw his father\u2019s reflection\u2014a proud man made small by circumstances. There were no grand speeches, just a shared, suffocating silence that said everything. That silence taught him that heartbreak wasn't always loud; sometimes it was the quiet turning of a key, locking away a lifetime of work.\n\n3.\nHis first shift bussing tables, a man of thirty surrounded by college kids. He was clearing a half-eaten plate of risotto, a dish he could have made better with his eyes closed. A well-dressed woman at the table glanced at him, her eyes flicking away with polite disinterest. The sting of humiliation was sharp. But as he stacked the plate in the tub, a harder feeling took over: resolve. He vowed then that no one in his restaurant would ever be made to feel invisible.\n\n4.\nHe remembers coming home near 2 AM, the exhaustion a familiar cloak. Her note was on the counter, propped against his favorite coffee mug. The wedding photo next to it was facedown. He stood in the crushing silence of the apartment, the quiet a stark contrast to the nightly chaos he orchestrated. He realized then that he had built a perfect restaurant but had let his own home crumble. The loneliness that settled in that night never truly left.\n\n5.\nJust last week, walking his usual route, he saw it: a small, grimy storefront with a faded \u201cFor Lease\u201d sign. For a second, the traffic noise faded, replaced by the imaginary clatter of plates and warm laughter. He could almost smell his father\u2019s Sunday gravy. He stopped, pulled out his phone, and looked at his savings account. The numbers weren't just digits anymore; they were bricks and mortar. They were a promise to himself. A way back home."
